<subSubSection id="2DD56497FFF0FFBDFF70FF1862C823D8" pageId="4" pageNumber="436" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6570371CFFF0FFBDFF70FF1862C823D8" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="57BBEB0EFFF0FFBDFF70FF1861472391" bold="true" box="[199,322,150,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from other species in this genus by the slender aedeagal shaft, with a pair of triangular preapical processes. The genus also has some resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="A2CF4C9FFFF0FFBDFB95FF3564DD23F4" authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" box="[1058,1240,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Tambila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="57BBEB0EFFF0FFBDFB95FF35647823F4" box="[1058,1149,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">Tambila</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter has the head in profile angled to the apex near the eye.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2DD56497FFF0FFBDFF70FE8D6581223C" box="[199,1412,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="436" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6570371CFFF0FFBDFF70FE8D6581223C" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,285]" box="[199,1412,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="57BBEB0EFFF0FFBDFF70FE8D614B223C" bold="true" box="[199,334,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">Etymology.</emphasis>
This specific epithet is from the 
<emphasis id="57BBEB0EFFF0FFBDFD08FE8D62FF223C" box="[703,762,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">Latin</emphasis>
word “ 
<emphasis id="57BBEB0EFFF0FFBDFCF9FE8D6385223D" box="[846,896,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="436">mini</emphasis>
” referring to the aedeagal shaft being slender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
